import{_ as t,c as a,o as i,a5 as o,eF as n,eG as s,eH as r,eI as l,eJ as c,eK as d,eL as g,eM as h,eN as p,eO as m,eP as b,eQ as u,eR as f,eS as _,eT as w,eU as y,eV as T}from"./chunks/framework.CgTIqH8g.js";const A=JSON.parse('{"title":"Advanced Table Editing","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"docs/guide-table.md","filePath":"docs/guide-table.md","lastUpdated":1761037405000}'),k={name:"docs/guide-table.md"};function P(x,e,v,M,q,S){return i(),a("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[o('<h1 id="advanced-table-editing" tabindex="-1">Advanced Table Editing <a class="header-anchor" href="#advanced-table-editing" aria-label="Permalink to “Advanced Table Editing”">​</a></h1><p><strong>Tables</strong> are very versatile layout &quot;building blocks&quot;. Liii STEM can not only create ordinary text tables but also precisely control the attributes of each cell; more broadly speaking, matrices, aligned formula lists, etc., are also typeset in the form of &quot;tables&quot;.</p><p>For methods of table <strong>insertion</strong> and <strong>referencing</strong>, see <a href="https://liiistem.com/docs/guide-lines.html" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Referencing Numbered Content</a>.</p><p>This guide will help you further master table usage methods and provide detailed introductions to <strong>matrices</strong> and <strong>piecewise functions</strong>.</p><h1 id="_1-tables" tabindex="-1">1 <strong>Tables</strong> <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-tables" aria-label="Permalink to “1 Tables”">​</a></h1><h2 id="_1-1-types-of-tables" tabindex="-1">1.1 Types of Tables <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-1-types-of-tables" aria-label="Permalink to “1.1 Types of Tables”">​</a></h2><ul><li><strong>Regular tables</strong> are conventional tables in the main text, without numbering or captions. They are classified based on width, centering, presence of labels, and borders.</li></ul><p><img src="'+n+'" alt="Regular Table"></p><ul><li><strong>Numbered tables</strong> have <strong>numbering and captions</strong>. <strong>Large tables</strong> occupy a single row, while <strong>small tables</strong> can be arranged side by side.</li></ul><p><img src="'+s+'" alt="Numbered Large Table"></p><p><img src="'+r+'" alt="Numbered Small Table"></p><h2 id="_1-2-basic-table-editing" tabindex="-1">1.2 Basic Table Editing <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-2-basic-table-editing" aria-label="Permalink to “1.2 Basic Table Editing”">​</a></h2><ul><li><strong>Insert Table</strong>: Click the <code>six-grid</code> style button in the Mode Toolbar (as shown below) and select the table type.</li></ul><p><img src="'+l+'" alt="Six-Grid Button"></p><ul><li><strong>Add/Delete Rows and Columns</strong>: Newly created tables are generally <code>1×1</code> empty tables. After selecting a table, the Environment Toolbar will display table-related operation sections.</li></ul><p><img src="'+c+'" alt="Add/Delete Rows and Columns"></p><p>The first four icons from left to right in the above image are: insert row above, insert column to the left, insert column to the right, insert row below; the last four are the corresponding deletion operations.</p><blockquote><p>Tips: Liii STEM has <strong>Magic Paste</strong> functionality that allows you to directly paste tables from AI Large Language Model responses. This greatly saves you time creating empty tables + entering content, generating with one click, efficient and convenient! <img src="'+d+'" alt=""><img src="'+g+'" alt=""></p></blockquote><h2 id="_1-3-modifying-table-properties" tabindex="-1">1.3 Modifying Table Properties <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-3-modifying-table-properties" aria-label="Permalink to “1.3 Modifying Table Properties”">​</a></h2><ul><li>In the Menu Bar, click <code>Format</code> -&gt; <code>Table</code> to open the <strong>Table Properties</strong></li><li>Or select the table and right-click to bring up the <strong>Function Bar</strong></li></ul><p><img src="'+h+'" alt=""><img src="'+p+'" alt=""></p><h3 id="_1-3-1-setting-row-and-column-count" tabindex="-1">1.3.1 Setting Row and Column Count <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-3-1-setting-row-and-column-count" aria-label="Permalink to “1.3.1 Setting Row and Column Count”">​</a></h3><p>You can set the number of rows and columns in the following three ways:</p><ul><li>Click buttons in the Environment Toolbar</li><li>Set &quot;Rows&quot; and &quot;Columns&quot; in the Table Properties window</li><li>Right-click to bring up the Function Bar and set in <code>Table</code> -&gt; <code>Size</code></li></ul><p>Additionally, you can declare <strong>minimum/maximum row and column counts</strong> for tables, making it easier to create custom table macros.</p><blockquote><p>Note: If the set value for row/column attributes exceeds their allowed minimum and maximum range, the setting will not take effect, and the corresponding row/column attributes of the table will remain unchanged.</p></blockquote><h3 id="_1-3-2-adjusting-width-and-height" tabindex="-1">1.3.2 Adjusting Width and Height <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-3-2-adjusting-width-and-height" aria-label="Permalink to “1.3.2 Adjusting Width and Height”">​</a></h3><p>The overall width and height of the table can be set in the Table Properties or the Function Bar&#39;s width/height settings.</p><p>There are two common global sizing strategies:</p><p><img src="'+m+'" alt=""><img src="'+b+'" alt=""></p><h3 id="_1-3-3-page-splitting" tabindex="-1">1.3.3 Page Splitting <a class="header-anchor" href="#_1-3-3-page-splitting" aria-label="Permalink to “1.3.3 Page Splitting”">​</a></h3><p>For long tables that span across pages, you can enable page splitting by clicking <code>Format</code> -&gt; <code>Table</code> -&gt; <code>Table Properties</code> -&gt; <code>Allow Page Break</code> in the Menu Bar.</p><p><img src="'+u+'" alt=""></p><blockquote><p>Note: If cells have borders set, it is recommended to set the <strong>line/paragraph spacing</strong> of that paragraph to <code>0</code> to avoid extra white space at page breaks.</p></blockquote><p><img src="'+f+'" alt=""><img src="'+_+'" alt=""></p><h1 id="_2-common-mathematical-applications-of-tables" tabindex="-1">2 Common Mathematical Applications of Tables <a class="header-anchor" href="#_2-common-mathematical-applications-of-tables" aria-label="Permalink to “2 Common Mathematical Applications of Tables”">​</a></h1><p>Matrices are presented in Liii STEM as special forms of tables: you can add/delete rows and columns, set alignment and dimensions like editing tables, and then choose the outer delimiters (parentheses, square brackets, vertical lines, etc.).</p><p>Therefore, the vast majority of table tool editing methods <strong>also apply</strong> to matrices, as detailed below:</p><h2 id="_2-1-matrices" tabindex="-1">2.1 Matrices <a class="header-anchor" href="#_2-1-matrices" aria-label="Permalink to “2.1 Matrices”">​</a></h2><p>In the Menu Bar, sequentially click <code>Insert</code> -&gt; <code>Math</code> -&gt; <code>Displayed/Inline Formula</code>.</p><p>Displayed formulas occupy an entire row, while inline formulas are embedded in the text.</p><p><img src="'+w+'" alt=""></p><p>In the formula environment, sequentially click <code>Insert</code> -&gt; <code>Table</code> -&gt; <code>Matrix</code> in the Menu Bar. This way, we generate a <code>1x1</code> empty matrix in the formula row, with other methods being the same as for <strong>tables</strong>.</p><p><img src="'+y+'" alt=""></p><h2 id="_2-2-piecewise-functions" tabindex="-1">2.2 Piecewise Functions <a class="header-anchor" href="#_2-2-piecewise-functions" aria-label="Permalink to “2.2 Piecewise Functions”">​</a></h2><p>Piecewise functions are essentially two-column tables with a <strong>large brace</strong> on the left side (left column for expressions, right column for conditions), so they can be handled using table editing methods. Specifically:</p><ul><li>In the Menu Bar, sequentially click <code>Insert</code> -&gt; <code>Math</code> -&gt; <code>Displayed/Inline Formula</code></li><li>Manually input the function name, equal sign, and other parts.</li><li>Use the command <strong>\\choice</strong> to insert the large brace and single-column table <blockquote><p>Small tip: You can quickly increase the number of rows by pressing Enter! The operations for adjusting rows and columns are the same as for <strong>tables</strong>.</p></blockquote></li><li>Input expressions and other information you need to enter.</li></ul><p><img src="'+T+'" alt=""></p>',48)])])}const B=t(k,[["render",P]]);export{A as __pageData,B as default};
